  	    "description": "In this week\u0027s column, The Style Guy offers advice to a sneakerhead\u0027s unhappy girlfriend, plus tips on pulling off throwback pants and dressing well for the wedding after-party  ",
  	    "articleBody": "My boyfriend is a sneakerhead, and I find it extremely annoying. I keep telling him that it\u0027s childish and expensive. He says I don\u0027t understand because I\u0027m a woman and only wear sneakers to the gym. When should a man give up chasing the latest sneakers?Let\u0027s establish a few things: \u000A\u000ALoving sneakers isn\u0027t childish……though it definitely is expensive. You don\u0027t understand being a sneakerhead because you\u0027re not into sneakers—not because you\u0027re a woman. We don\u0027t let swerves perpetuate misogyny in this column. NOT IN MY HOUSE. [Mutombo finger wag]\u000A\u000AListen, I can see why you look at sneakerheads, your boyfriend included, as obsessive. I mean, Flight Club just launched a layaway program. The sneaker game has boiled over in some very extreme ways. But everybody loves something. Foodies. Watch collectors. Car nerds. Yeah, that passion can trip over into greed, but unless your boyfriend is spending your rent money on Jordans, I don\u0027t see the problem. If it\u0027s his money, and you\u0027re not being buried by box-fresh Yeezy Boosts every time you open a closet door, why take away something he enjoys? Think of it from his side: You only have one, maybe two, pairs of sneakers, right? And yet he accepts you and isn\u0027t writing advice columnists about your piss-poor sneaker game. So maybe just rise up and love through this.  \u000A\u000AFacebookPinterest\u000A\u000ALately I\u0027ve been digging Leon Bridges\u0027 throwback \u002760s style. I\u0027m a big guy, though—250 pounds, but in shape—so finding high-waisted pants is impossible. Help?Ever since the movie Her was released and showed us our phone-fornicating future, I\u0027ve felt like every guy should have at least one pair of high-waisted pants—including you, big fella. They\u0027re a way to stand out in even the most basic outfit. The key to killing high-waisted pants is that they have to be slim, all the way down to the hem. (Leon Bridges, the smooth criminal, is stick-thin and can get away with his signature extra-wide pants. I\u0027d advise staying away from those.) To find your own pair, stop by a Brooks Brothers or your town\u0027s best old-school, no-nonsense haberdashery—you know, where the salesmen have as many liver spots as they do ties—and ask for pants in their most conservative fit. Chances are those pants will have a long rise—but some wider legs. Swing by the tailor and put him to tapering. If you\u0027re really committed, you can scout for a vintage pair. This is the rare moment when eBay won\u0027t work for you—you\u0027ll have to try on a bunch of pairs so you know for certain that you\u0027ll make Leon and Joaquin proud.  \u000A\u000AI\u0027ve been invited to a wedding where the ceremony\u0027s dress code is listed as \u0022upscale casual.\u0022 After the reception everyone\u0027s heading to a drag show at a bar. (Go Supreme Court—a legal gay wedding!) I want to follow the dress code without looking too nerdy, since I\u0027m single. What do I wear?First, let\u0027s toast one time to love winning, ya dig? Okay. \u0022Upscale casual\u0022 isn\u0027t a real thing. That\u0027s the \u0022jumbo shrimp\u0022 of dress codes. But it\u0027s your friends\u0027 day, so we\u0027ll figure it out. I vote that you wear cocktail attire to both the ceremony and the after-party—but still go for a costume change. Bring two suits, one light for everything up through the reception, one dark for the actual wedding. I\u0027m 27, which means I basically went on a world tour of weddings this summer. I wore the same suit to every single one (that wasn\u0027t black tie): a medium-gray hopsack two-piece from Boglioli. I went with black brogues and a white shirt and air tie or just a white T-shirt, depending on how dressy the vibe was. But if you want to go bolder, you could pair your suit with a fine-knit turtleneck, clean designer sneakers, or an exploded-print button-up—not all at once, obviously—and still nail whatever fabricated, \u0022upscale casual Armageddon-chic\u0022 dress code you come across. \u000A\u000A\u000A\u000AThe GQ Style Guy Is In! Send questions to Styleguy@GQ.com or tweet @GQStyleGuy\u000A\u000AFor more style tips, order our new GQ Style Guide.",
  	    "author": ["Mark Anthony Green"],
